    <etym xml:lang="ru">Слово не может быть сближаемо с иранскими и индоевропейскими названиями
        соли. Как некоторые другие важные культурные термины, имеет связи, с одной стороны, с
        кавказскими, с другой — угро-финскими языками (ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_ændon"/>
        ‘сталь’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kaw"/> ʼплетеньʼ, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kært"
        /> ‘двор’). На кавказской почве сопоставлялись <mentioned xml:lang="av"
            ><lang/><w>can</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ani"><lang/><w>con</w></mentioned>,
        ср. также <mentioned xml:lang="ddo"><lang/><w>tciō</w></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="lbe"><lang/><w>tcu</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"
            ><lang/><w>ʒi</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="dar"><w>ce</w></mentioned>, ,
            <mentioned xml:lang="ab"><lang/><w>a-ǯəkʼa</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="uby"
                ><lang/><w>ǯə</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"
            ><lang/><w>šuǧu</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ady-x-abadz"
            ><lang/><w>šuǧö</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ady"
            ><lang/><w>šugu</w></mentioned>. На угро-финской почве: <mentioned xml:lang="mns"
                ><lang/><w>šäx</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="mns"><w>śax</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang="mns"><w>ćix</w></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="yrk"
                ><lang/><w>šak</w><note type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note type="comment"
                xml:lang=""> ()</note></mentioned>. Носовой %in%i в <mentioned xml:lang="os-x-digor"
                ><lang/><w>cænxæ</w></mentioned>, поддерживаемый аварским <mentioned xml:lang="av"
                ><lang/><w>can</w></mentioned>, следует рассматривать как старое (а не вторичное,
        чисто дигорское) явление; иначе трудно было бы оправдать геминацию %iх%i в иронском
            <mentioned xml:lang="os-x-iron"><lang/><w>cæxx</w></mentioned> (ср. <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_zæxx"/> | %izænxæ%i ‘земля’). А раз так, то отношения осетинской формы к
        угро-финским требуют доследования.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_MSt."
            /><biblScope>85</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                /><biblScope>314</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">The word cannot be related to Iranian and Indo-European names of salt. Like
        some other important cultural terms, the word has connections, on one hand, with Caucasian
        languages, on the other hand — with Finno-Ugric languages (cf. <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_ændon"/> ‘steel’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kaw"/> ʼwattleʼ, <ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_kært"/> ‘yard’). The following languages show evidence of
        Caucasian origin: <mentioned xml:lang="av"><lang/><w>can</w></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="ani"><lang/><w>con</w></mentioned>, cf. also <mentioned xml:lang="ddo"
                ><lang/><w>tciō</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lbe"
            ><lang/><w>tcu</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"
            ><lang/><w>ʒi</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="dar"><w>ce</w></mentioned>, ,
            <mentioned xml:lang="ab"><lang/><w>a-ǯəkʼa</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="uby"
                ><lang/><w>ǯə</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"
            ><lang/><w>šuǧu</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ady-x-abadz"
            ><lang/><w>šuǧö</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ady"
            ><lang/><w>šugu</w></mentioned>. The following words are comparable in Finno-Ugric
        languages: <mentioned xml:lang="mns"><lang/><w>šäx</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="mns"
                ><w>śax</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="mns"><w>ćix</w></mentioned>, ,
            <mentioned xml:lang="yrk"><lang/><w>šak</w><note type="comment" xml:lang="">
                ()</note><note type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note></mentioned>. The nasal %in%i in
            <mentioned xml:lang="os-x-digor"><lang/><w>cænxæ</w></mentioned> , which is also found
        in Avar <mentioned xml:lang="av"><lang/><w>can</w></mentioned>, should be considered as an
        old (and not secondary, only Digor) feature; otherwise it would be hard to justify the
        gemination of %iх%i in Iron <mentioned xml:lang="os-x-iron"><lang/><w>cæxx</w></mentioned>
        (cf. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_zæxx"/> | %izænxæ%i ‘soil’). If so, the relationship of
        the Ossetic form to the Finno-Ugric form requires further investigation.%n<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_MSt."/><biblScope>85</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref
                target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>314</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
